## Summary

I have successfully implemented the `containsInvalidHeaderChar` utility in `/testbed/lib/utils.js`.

### Implementation Added

```javascript
exports.containsInvalidHeaderChar = function containsInvalidHeaderChar(value) {
  if (value === null || value === undefined) {
    return false;
  }

  if (Array.isArray(value)) {
    for (var i = 0; i < value.length; i++) {
      if (containsInvalidHeaderChar(value[i])) {
        return true;
      }
    }
    return false;
  }

  var str = String(value);
  // Check for literal CR, LF and escaped sequences (\r, \n)
  return /[\r\n]|\\r|\\n/.test(str);
};
```

### Input Type Handling

| Type | Handling | Example |
|------|----------|---------|
| `null`, `undefined` | Returns `false` (no invalid chars) | `null` → `false` |
| Strings | Checks for literal CR/LF (`\r`, `\n`) AND escaped (`\\r`, `\\n`) | `"foo\rbar"` → `true`, `"foo\\rbar"` → `true` |
| Arrays | Recursively checks all elements | `["a", "b\r"]` → `true`, nested arrays supported |
| Numbers, Booleans | Converted to string via `String()` | `123` → `false` |

### Export Status
✅ **Exported** via `exports.containsInvalidHeaderChar` - can be imported by other modules using `require('./lib/utils').containsInvalidHeaderChar`.

This utility now serves as the single source of truth for CRLF validation across the Express request/response paths.
